# nl-rag distilled facts вЂ” domain: abkhaz-alphabet
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/1829-braille] Louis Braille's original publication, *Procedure for Writing Words, Music, and Plainsong in Dots* (1829), credits Barbier's night writing as being the basis for the braille script.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/1829-braille] It differed in a fundamental way from modern braille: It contained nine decades (series) of characters rather than the modern five, utilizing dashes as well as dots.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/1829-braille] Braille recognized, however, that the dashes were problematic, being difficult to distinguish from the dots in practice, and those characters were abandoned in the second edition of the book.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/1829-braille] The first four decades indicated the 40 letters of the alphabet (39 letters of the French alphabet, plus English *w*); the fifth the digits; the sixth punctuation; and the seventh and part of the eighth mathematical symbols.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/1829-braille] The seventh decade was also used for musical notes.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/1829-braille] Most of the remaining characters were unassigned.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/1829-braille] Thus the 1st and 5th decades occupied only the top half of the cell, while all characters in the other decades had a dot or dash in the bottom row.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/1829-braille] The supplemental signs were в „в ¤в њв ј and a top dash with в  в °.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/1829-braille] Of the 125 (53) possible patterns, 97 were used.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/1829-braille] The modern 5th decade and other supplemental signs do not appear in the 1829 version of braille, apart from в ђ and в ’ in plainsong notation.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/1829-braille] Anticipating that the dashes might prove problematic, Braille provided that the supplemental sign в ј (now known as the number sign) would shift the decade by four.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/1829-braille] That is, adding it to the first four decades would produce substitutes for the fifth through eighth.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/1829-braille] Only its use to replace the old fifth decade has been retained; the old sixth decade survives as the modern fifth, with the dash removed and the dots shifted down to replace it.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/1829-braille] The book allots a great deal of space to the representation of music.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/1829-braille] Instrumental notation was largely a one-to-one transcription of the system already in use for the blind.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/1829-braille] The durations of the notes and the accidentals, however, had to be replaced; for these the 7th decade was used, as shown in the table above.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/1829-braille] A simplified system for plainsong was provided.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/1829-braille] The twelve notes are the twelve characters of the upper half of the cell (the first and fifth decades) which do not have dashes.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/1829-braille] By themselves (1st decade), they indicate half notes.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/1829-braille] Quarter notes are 2nd decade, dotted quarter notes 3rd, and eighth notes 4th.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/1829-braille] Dotted half notes are indicated by a dash below (6th decade), whole notes by a dash above (7th decade), and dotted whole notes by a mid dash (8th decade).
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/1829-braille] The alto, bass, treble, and tenor clefs were indicated by the 5thвЂ“8th characters of the fifth decade. в ђ is the sharp-note prefix, в ’ the bass-note prefix, and the equivalent with a dash the natural prefix. в „в ¤ are the repetition sign and 'star'.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/1829-braille] The book finishes with a proposal for braille shorthand, utilizing the first decade for vowels, and the fifth for consonants (without a voicing distinction).
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/1829-braille] That is, Braille's shorthand used a 4-dot cell rather than the standard 6-dot cell, taking two-thirds the space of normal braille, and one-third the space of Barbier's night writing.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/1829-braille] In the classroom, Braille's students found the characters with dashes to be impractical, as the dashes were not easily distinguishable from pairs of dots, and they were quickly abandoned.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/1829-braille] The second edition of the *ProcГ©dГ©*, published in 1837, sets out French Braille essentially as we know it today.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/1829-braille] According to Henri (1952), at right, the numerical sign was used with the new fifth decade, plus one of the supplementary characters, for mathematical notation: в јв – +, в јв ¤ в€’, в јв ¦ Г—, в јв І /, в јв ¶ =, в јв њ в€љ.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/1829-braille] Several of these values continue today in Antoine notation.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/1829-braille] The official Unicode encoding for Braille only specifies codepoints for modern dot-only patterns.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/1829-braille] An unofficial encoding for dash patterns can be found in the Under-ConScript Unicode Registry, and as such may be found in some fonts that cover characters from that agreement.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/1829-braille] Together, these two blocks can represent all cell definitions from the 1829 Braille specification.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/a-cyrillic] The Cyrillic letter Рђ was derived directly from the Greek letter Alpha (О‘ О±).
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/a-cyrillic] In the Early Cyrillic alphabet its name was Р°Р·СЉ (azЗ”), meaning the personal pronoun "I".
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/a-cyrillic] In the Cyrillic numeral system, the Cyrillic letter Рђ has a value of 1.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/a-cyrillic] Throughout history, the Cyrillic letter Рђ has had various shapes, but today is standardized on one that looks exactly like the Latin letter A, including the italic and lower case forms.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/a-cyrillic] In most languages that use the Cyrillic alphabet вЂ“ such as Bulgarian, Ukrainian, Belarusian, Russian, Rusyn, Serbian, Macedonian and Montenegrin вЂ“ the Cyrillic letter Рђ represents the open central unrounded vowel /a/.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/a-cyrillic] In Ingush and Chechen, the Cyrillic letter Рђ represents both the open back unrounded vowel /Й‘/ when stressed and the mid-central vowel /Й™/ when unstressed.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/a-cyrillic] In Turkic languages that use the Cyrillic script it represents the open back unrounded vowel /Й‘/, with the exception of Volga Tatar, in which it represents the open back rounded vowel /Й’/, and Uzbek, in which it represents the near-open front unrounded vowel /Г¦/.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/a-cyrillic] In languages that contrast vowel length the letter can be written as double vowel.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/a-with-breve-cyrillic] It is used in the Chuvash and in both Eastern Khanty and Northern Khanty alphabets.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/a-with-breve-cyrillic] It appears in some Nenets dictionaries as well.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/a-with-breve-cyrillic] In certain orthographical varieties of Bulgarian, such as in the Primer with Various Instructions, this letter was used for the sound /Й¤/.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/a-with-breve-cyrillic] In modern Bulgarian, this sound is represented by the letter РЄ.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/a-with-breve-cyrillic] In Chuvash, вџЁУ‘вџ© represents the mid central vowel [Й™], as вџЁaвџ© in word "er**a**".
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/a-with-breve-cyrillic] It is always reduced and can occur stressed only in the first syllable of a polysyllabic word.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/a-with-breve-cyrillic] The sound varies in its phonetic realization from a reduced /i/ or [Й™] (like the pronunciation of вџЁaвџ© in English "sof**a**") to a labialized version of the вџЁaвџ© in English "**a**ll" (with rounded lips).
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/a-with-breve-cyrillic] It is sometimes so reduced as to sound coalesced with the following consonant as in СЃУ‘С‚РµР» *table*, /stel/.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/a-with-circumflex-cyrillic] Nineteenth century polymath Mykhailo Maksymovych used an orthography for the Ukrainian language based on etymological principles of spelling, which included the letter РђМ‚ .
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/a-with-circumflex-cyrillic] This letter is also used in some dialects of South Slavic languages such as Bulgarian and Serbian (e.g. РіР»Р°М‚РІР° or РєСЂР°М‚Рє).
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/a-with-circumflex-cyrillic] Being a relatively recent letter, not present in any legacy 8-bit Cyrillic encoding, the letter РђМ‚ is not represented directly by a precomposed character in Unicode either; it has to be composed as Рђ+в—ЊМ‚ (U+0302).
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] It is used in the Khanty, Kildin Sami, Ter Sami, and Hill Mari languages.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] Also, this letter was once used in the Gagauz language (which was substituted with вџЁР°СЊвџ©).
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] It was used in the Bashkir language at the end of the 19th century.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] It corresponds to the Cyrillic letter schwa вџЁУ™вџ© in modern Bashkir.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] This letter also appears in Bulgarian and Serbian in some of its dialects.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] In Hill Mari and Gagauz this letter represents the near-open front unrounded vowel, /Г¦/.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] In Kildin Sami and Ter Sami this letter represents the open back unrounded vowel /a/ following a palatalized (sometimes also called "half-palatalized") velar nasal /nКІ/ or one of the alveolar stops /tКІ/ or /dКІ/.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] In Khanty this letter represents the near-open central vowel /Йђ/.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] Some languages represent as /ja/, like in letter "РЇ".
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] A with diaeresis is used in some South Slavic languages, mainly in the Bulgarian and Serbian language to be used for easily shifting the accents in the above languages not only in declensions but elsewhere: Р±СЂУ“С‚ or РјР»ДЃРґГ¤.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/a-with-macron-cyrillic] A with macron is used in the Aleut (Bering dialect), Evenki, Ingush, Mansi, Nanai, Orok, Ulch, Kildin Sami, Selkup, and Chechen languages.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/a-with-macron-cyrillic] A with macron also appears in the Bulgarian and Serbian languages in some dialects.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/a-with-macron-cyrillic] A with macron is used in the South Slavic languages mostly in Bulgarian usually used before or after another stressed vowel: **РіР»ДЃРІГ **, **РєСЂДЃРєГ **, **РѕРІС‡ДЃСЂГЁ**, **РєРѕРІДЃС‡ГЁ**, **СЋРЅДЃС†Сќ**, and **РіСЂР°Р¶РґДЃРЅГЁ**.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/a-with-macron-cyrillic] Being a relatively recent letter, not present in any legacy 8-bit Cyrillic encoding, the letter РђМ„ is not represented directly by a precomposed character in Unicode either; it has to be composed as Рђ+в—ЊМ„ (U+0304).
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] The current **Abkhaz alphabet** is a modified variant of the Cyrillic script used for the Abkhaz language.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] Abkhaz was not a written language until the 19th century.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] Until then, AbkhaziansвЂ”especially elitesвЂ”had been using Greek (until c.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] 9th century), Georgian (9вЂ“19th centuries), and partially Turkish (18th century).
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] The first Abkhaz alphabet was created in 1862 by Peter von Uslar.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] It had 55 letters and was based on the Cyrillic script.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] Another version, having 51 letters, was used in 1892 by Dimitry Gulia and K.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] In 1909, the alphabet was again expanded to 55 letters by Andria Tchotchua to adjust to the extensive consonantal inventory of Abkhaz.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] In 1926, during the *korenizatsiya* policy in the Soviet Union, the Cyrillic alphabet was replaced by a Latin alphabet devised by Nikolay Marr.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] It featured 76 letters and was called the "Abkhaz analytical alphabet".
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] In 1928, this was replaced by another Latin alphabet.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] From 1938 to 1954 the Abkhaz language was written in Georgian *Mkhedruli script*.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] Since 1954, the Abkhaz language has been written in a new 58-letter (now 64-letter) Cyrillic alphabet (see chart below).
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] Of these, 38 are graphically distinct; the rest are digraphs with вџЁСЊвџ© and вџЁУ™вџ© which indicate palatalization and labialization, respectively.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] In 1996, the most recent reform of the alphabet was implemented: while labialization had hitherto been marked with two additional letters, У™ and Сѓ (Сѓ was used in the digraphs РіСѓ, Т•Сѓ, РєСѓ, Т›Сѓ, ТџСѓ, and С…Сѓ, which were not considered separate letters), since then only У™ was retained in this function.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] Unusually, the Cyrillic plosive letters Рє Рї С‚ represent ejective consonants; the non-ejectives (pulmonic consonants) are derived from these by means of a descender at the bottom of the letter.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] In the case of the affricates, however, the plain letters are pulmonic, and the derived letters ejective.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] The modern Abkhaz orthography gives preference to the letters Рі Рє Рї С‚ С… С‡ with descender (У· Т› ФҐ Т­ Ті Т·).
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] The letters (Т• Т§) had previously (before 1996) had a hook, which Т• still does in Yakut.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] In pre-Soviet alphabets the hook was also used in У„ кљ‹, see above.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] The letters СЊ and У™ are used as parts of digraphs, but are listed separately in the alphabet.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] Besides the digraphs listed in the alphabet, the letter СЊ occurs in Р»СЊ /lКІ/, which is used in some loanwords.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] Letters or digraphs in brackets are not part of the alphabet.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] Letters without a modern equivalent represent phonemes only present in the Bzyb dialect, as the literary standard dialect switched from Bzyb to Abzhywa.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] Its core components are digits, locatives, marks and movements which are written in a fairly rigid order (though in a fairly flexible configuration) from left to right.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] The order of the writing is from left to right, top to bottom, with locatives or certain marks often beginning words.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] Sentences are ended by the full stop mark ().
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] Questions in written ASL are denoted by eyebrow marks bounding the question not unlike Spanish's "Вї ?." Question words or wh-questions in ASL can also form the interrogative.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] There are in total 105 characters in ASLwrite with 67 digits, five diacritic marks, twelve locatives, sixteen extramanual marks and five movement marks.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] Since its creation, it has evolved to include more digits, locatives, movements and marks as well as modify those already present.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] si5s, a system built from SignWriting, was first proposed by Robert Arnold in his 2007 Gallaudet thesis *A Proposal of the Written System for ASL*.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] The ASLwrite community split from Arnold upon his decision to maintain si5s as a private venture with ASLized after the publication of his and Adrean Clark's book *How to Write American Sign Language*.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] Aside from the small, but dedicated, Facebook group of around 470 in July 2023, ASLwrite is rarely used outside such online spaces.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] However, one of the most popular online ASL dictionaries, HandSpeak, has begun to incorporate ASLwrite as the primary written component of ASL definitions.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] ASLwrite is a somacheirographic system meaning that it represents the body (Greek: Пѓбї¶ОјО± *sГґma* 'body') and hands (Greek: П‡ОµОЇПЃ *kheГ­r* 'hand') and relays phonemic information.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] However, it also incorporates logographs (questioning marks) and is featural.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] The general principle is to capture a single ASL word per segment, from left to right, registering non-manual feature(s), location(s), handshape(s), movement(s) and general orientation.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] It imagines the writer/speaker is looking down at their hands or viewing words from the profile such that words can be made either as if seen from straight-on or from one's profile.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] The digibet captures handshape information as well as orientation, movement and some locations.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] Locatives are characters that capture location, though handshape diacritics like *edge* do capture some locations such as edge of palm.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] Diacritics, such as movements, modify handshapes and can indicate small movements or small orientations.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] Movements themselves are fairly flexible in their shapes and orientations, which makes digitising this script difficult.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] Frontal or profile locatives вЂ“ Captures the same location information, just from two perspectives.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] An example (seen on the right) is the shoulder locative is either a shoulder frontal locative that is written above or below the handshape(s).
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] Handshapes вЂ“ Can be written before or after the locative.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] A handshape can be oriented in 360В° depending on its location and is written at the end of its movement path if there is one.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] Each handshape present is written, and when more than one handshape (of one hand) is written, a movement must be present.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] Movements вЂ“ Larger movements or movements that affect multiple handshapes.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] When a handshape changes without overt movement, the handshapes are written left-to-right with a single movement below, similar to an underline.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] Non-manual & punctuation marks вЂ“ These are questioning marks such as *why*, *who*, *how* and *how*.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] The digibet is composed of handshapes called digits that are modified by diacritics and movements.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] It shares 23 handshapes with ASL's manual alphabet.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] Digits are grouped together by features such as +thumb/-thumb or +closed/-closed.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] In practise, there are 67 digits in ASLwrite's digibet, though that number is growing as new digits are added representing diverse handshapes.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] Moreover, other languages may adopt this system which would add increasingly more digits.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] There are five diacritics, of which one is a movement diacritic.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] Movements are flexible and thus hard to capture in a digital or non-handwritten fashion.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] The movements are diverse and aim to capture the movements of the hands, arms and body.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] There are three points вЂ“ an **endpoint**, a **firmpoint** and a **contactpoint** вЂ“, an **orbit mark**, a **steering** and a **crank mark** as well as the movement mark or line.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] The movement line follows the path of the hand(s) and can be as clean (e.g., вЂ“ or | ) or as erratic as possible.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] The points denote the end of a handshape's path and the degree to which the motion is made.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] A contactpoint denotes an imaginary or in-the-air point with the contactpoint ending at a location and noted as being a firm ending with the firmpoint.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] The orbit mark indicates a central "point" around which the handshapes orbit; for orbital paths cut short, one would use a steering mark, and for parallel cranking motions, the crank mark would be used.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] The locatives are characters that denote a specific location on or near the signer's body.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] They are presented from a face-on and side-view.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] The two sub-classifications are **frontal** and **profile locatives**.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] Non-manual marks vary quite significantly and can only be placed at the beginning or end of words or phrases.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] **Eyebrow marks** are denoted before and after the word(s) in question thus bounding the words that are modified by eyebrow marks.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] They are called: **Raised (), Knit, Wan, Slanted** and **Squint**.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] Questioning marks exist in ASL as logographs that denote ASL's wh-questions such as WHO or FOR-FOR.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] They are placed after a closed word's or phrase's second eyebrow mark and can exist as an entire sentence alone.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] Mouth marks are characters that relay what action the mouth is doing.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] It is placed inside the first eyebrow mark.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] Body movements are non-manual, non-facial features such as **shoulder shift ()** or **head nod**.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] They, as well as **nose crinkle ()**, stand alone and can be inserted anywhere, inside and outside of eyebrow-marked phrases.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] means *Yes?* in ASL composed of , , and where the raised eyebrow marks at the beginning and the end indicate it is a yes/no question, and the hinge mark () denotes that the S handshape digit () makes a nodding motion.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] The circular point at the end is a full stop mark indicating the end of the sentence.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] Unlike in English writing, the full stop mark () is employed for all sentences, even questions (as seen here).
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] Breaks in the sentence, as seen below, are denoted by the shoulder shift mark ().
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] The text on the right is from Chapters 1:2вЂ“4 of the Book of Ruth.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] The first quoted text is the verse in English and the second is an ASL gloss.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] Due to the complexity of the writing system and its need for flexibility for movements, it means that producing anything in a digital format is difficult.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] However, there are efforts to create fonts headed by members of its Facebook group, notably looking at proper font creation and using current keyboard characters such as ' } ' or ' _.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] ' to achieve minor forms of communication in ASL over text.
[src:abkhaz-alphabet/aslwrite] An example phrase is " }_.U- " which means 'thank you' in ASL.
